power: therefore no human power can bind us to anything which is wicked, and so, contrary to the will of God. Whence Augustine says, that an unjust Law is hardly a Law.

And hence the answer to the argument, that obedience is not disputatious. The subject is to submit himself to the supreme authority without disputing it, but not to any subordinate autho-

rity, when contrary to the supreme. And, thus, we must obey God always.

So Abraham obeyed the command of God, and did what, not so commanded, would have been wrong and wicked. But the commands of men are to be examined. 1 Thess. v. 21, applies to commands as well as doctrines. Hence we reject absolutely authority, such as papists ascribe to the Pope, and religious orders to their Heads.
